ORIGINAL = {
  "1": {
    "4": "<p><strong>vesomach yado al rosh haolah veratzon lo lekapper alav</strong>: 'He shall lay his hand on the head of the burnt offering, and it shall be accepted for him to make atonement for him.' The <em>semikah</em> (laying of hands) is the key act of self-identification with the sacrifice: the offerer transfers his identity to the animal, which then represents him before YHWH. The term <em>kopher</em> (ransom/atonement, verb <em>kipper</em>) has its root either in 'to cover' or 'to ransom/substitute' (the latter supported by the Semitic cognate). The NT takes both senses: Christ's blood covers/forgives sin (Col 2:13-14) and he gives his life as a ransom (<em>lytron</em>) for many (Mark 10:45).</p>"
  },
  "8": {
    "1": "<p>YHWH commands Moses to take Aaron and his sons with the vestments, anointing oil, and the animals for ordination. The divine initiative is the key theological point: ordination comes by divine summons, not human ambition. Heb 5:4: &ldquo;one does not take this honor for himself, but only when called by God, just as Aaron was&rdquo; — the legitimacy of priesthood rests on being called, not on self-promotion.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The materials of ordination include the priestly garments, the <strong>shemen hamishchah</strong> (<em>šemen hammiššāḥ</em>, anointing oil), the bull for the sin offering, and the two rams. The unleavened bread (<em>maṣṣôt</em>) connects the priestly ordination to Passover purity; the new priesthood begins in the context of redemption and sinlessness (1 Cor 5:8 &ldquo;sincerity and truth&rdquo;).</p>",
    "3": "<p>Moses assembles all the congregation at the entrance of the tent of meeting — ordination is a public, corporate act witnessed by all Israel. The public nature of priestly consecration is essential: those who serve the community before YHWH are accountable to the community (1 Tim 3:2; Titus 1:6 &ldquo;above reproach&rdquo;).</p>",
    "4": "<p>&ldquo;Moses did as YHWH commanded him&rdquo; — the chapter's repeated refrain; Moses's precise obedience validates every subsequent step. No element is improvised; the entire ceremony is a replication of divine prescription. The pattern governs; creativity is not invited in the holy place.</p>",
    "5": "<p>&ldquo;This is the thing that YHWH has commanded to be done&rdquo; — Moses announces the divine authority behind the ritual before beginning. The declaratory formula grounds the ceremony in divine command rather than human tradition; the ordination's legitimacy is revelatory, not customary.</p>",
    "6": "<p>Moses washed Aaron and his sons with water — <strong>rachats</strong> (<em>rāḥaṣ</em>), washing/bathing; the water-washing is the first act of consecration, prerequisite to all that follows. Three elements mark priestly consecration: water (washing), oil (anointing), blood (sacrifice). 1 John 5:6-8 echoes a threefold witness of Spirit, water, and blood in the testimony to Christ; Heb 10:22 calls believers to draw near with &ldquo;hearts sprinkled clean... and bodies washed with pure water.&rdquo;</p>",
    "7": "<p>Moses clothed Aaron in the tunic (<em>kuttonet</em>), sash (<em>ʾavnet</em>), robe (<em>mêʿil</em>), ephod, and breastpiece, with the ephod's band tied around him. The vesting sequence invests Aaron with the symbolic clothing of office; Paul's clothing metaphor applies the same logic: &ldquo;put on the Lord Jesus Christ&rdquo; (Rom 13:14); believers are invested with Christ's righteousness as their priestly vestment (Gal 3:27).</p>",
    "8": "<p>Moses placed the breastpiece (<em>ḥōšen</em>) on Aaron with the <strong>Urim and Thummim</strong> (<em>hāʾûrîm wᵉhattummîm</em>) — the priestly oracular objects; the exact mechanism of their use is unknown, but they mediated divine decisions for the community (1 Sam 28:6). Christ as the ultimate oracular priest in whom &ldquo;are hidden all the treasures of wisdom and knowledge&rdquo; (Col 2:3) fulfills the oracular function of the Urim and Thummim permanently.</p>",
    "9": "<p>Moses set the turban (<em>miṣnepet</em>) on Aaron's head with the <strong>tzitz hazahav</strong> (<em>ṣîṣ hazzāhāv</em>), the golden plate inscribed <em>qōdeš laYHWH</em> (&ldquo;Holy to YHWH&rdquo;). The high priest bore YHWH's name on his forehead before the divine presence, presenting it on behalf of all Israel. Rev 22:4: servants of God will see his face and &ldquo;his name will be on their foreheads&rdquo; — the eschatological fulfillment of the high priest's golden crown applied to all new covenant priests.</p>",
    "10": "<p>Moses took the <strong>shemen hamishchah</strong> (<em>šemen hammiššāḥ</em>) and anointed the tabernacle and all its furnishings, consecrating them — the anointing of physical objects makes them sacred through the same oil that consecrates persons. The oil is the Spirit's material type; the Spirit's consecrating work makes what it touches holy. The tabernacle's anointing is the precursor of the Spirit's indwelling of the church-as-temple (1 Cor 3:16).</p>",
    "11": "<p>Moses sprinkled some of the anointing oil on the altar <strong>seven times</strong> (<em>ševaʿ pᵉʿāmîm</em>) — seven-fold sprinkling = complete and perfect consecration; the number seven throughout Leviticus signals fullness and completion. Christ's once-for-all sacrifice is the complete and final consecration of the true altar (Heb 10:14 &ldquo;by a single offering he has perfected for all time&rdquo;).</p>",
    "12": "<p>Moses poured the anointing oil on Aaron's head — <strong>yitzok shemen hamishchah al rosh Aharon</strong> (<em>wayyiṣōq miššemen hammiššāḥ ʿal rōʾš ʾahărōn</em>): &ldquo;he poured the anointing oil on Aaron's head.&rdquo; This act is the origin of the title <em>māšîaḥ</em> (Anointed One / Messiah); the anointing of Aaron's head made him high priest in perpetuity. Ps 45:7 / Heb 1:9 applies the divine anointing &ldquo;with the oil of gladness&rdquo; to Christ; Acts 10:38 identifies Jesus as the one God &ldquo;anointed with the Holy Spirit and with power.&rdquo;</p>",
    "13": "<p>Moses clothed Aaron's sons in simpler vestments — tunics (<em>kuttōnōt</em>), sashes, and caps (<em>migbāʿôt</em>) — as YHWH commanded. The sons of Aaron are dressed differently from the high priest: a hierarchy of holiness and responsibility within the priesthood. In Christ, all believers are priests (1 Pet 2:9) with equal access, but Christ alone wears the full high-priestly vestments of perfect intercession (Heb 7:26-28).</p>",
    "14": "<p>Aaron and his sons laid their hands on the head of the <strong>bull of the sin offering</strong> (<em>par haḥaṭṭāʾt</em>) — even the high priest requires a sin offering for his own sins before the ordination proceeds. <em>Ḥaṭṭāʾt</em> (sin offering) is derived from the root <em>ḥēt</em> (sin) — the offering is literally the &ldquo;sin-thing&rdquo;; the animal carries the identity of what it removes. Heb 7:27: &ldquo;He has no need, like those high priests, to offer sacrifices daily, first for his own sins and then for those of the people.&rdquo;</p>",
    "15": "<p>Moses put the blood on the <strong>horns of the altar</strong> (<em>qarnôt hammizbêaḥ</em>) with his finger and poured the rest at the base — blood on the four horns purifies the altar itself; the instrument of sacrifice must be consecrated before it can accept offerings. The base-pour returns the excess blood to the ground; blood is YHWH's (Lev 17:11), and the earth receives what is not burned.</p>",
    "16": "<p>Moses burned the <strong>chelev</strong> (<em>ḥēlev</em>, fat) on the altar — the fat portions belong to YHWH in every offering (Lev 3:16 &ldquo;all fat is YHWH's&rdquo;). The fat represents the richest, best portion of the animal; offering the fat to YHWH is offering the firstfruits of life's abundance. The NT parallel: &ldquo;offer your bodies as a living sacrifice&rdquo; (Rom 12:1) — the best of oneself as the ongoing offering.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The bull's flesh, skin, and dung were burned outside the camp — the sin offering carcass is entirely destroyed outside the sacred precincts; nothing remains that might contaminate. Heb 13:11-13: &ldquo;the bodies of those animals whose blood is brought into the holy places by the high priest as a sacrifice for sin are burned outside the camp. So Jesus also suffered outside the gate.&rdquo; The burning outside the camp is fulfilled in the crucifixion outside Jerusalem.</p>",
    "18": "<p>The <strong>ram of the burnt offering</strong> (<em>ʾêl hāʿōlāh</em>) — <em>ʿōlāh</em> from <em>ʿālāh</em> (to go up); the entire burnt offering ascends to YHWH in smoke; complete consecration of everything to God, holding nothing back. The burnt offering has no portion for the offerer; it is entirely devoted. Christ's total self-giving: &ldquo;who gave himself for us&rdquo; (Titus 2:14), without reservation.</p>",
    "19": "<p>Moses threw (<strong>zaraq</strong>, <em>zāraq</em>) the blood against the sides of the altar all around — the vigorous dashing of blood stands in contrast to the careful finger-application of the sin offering (v15); different application methods signal different functions: the sin offering's finger-dab is precise and priestly; the burnt offering's blood-dash is complete and comprehensive.</p>",
    "20": "<p>Moses cut the ram into pieces and burned the head, the pieces, and the fat on the altar — the systematic total-offering: every part of the burnt-offering ram is consumed; nothing remains. The completeness of the offering models total consecration. The NT parallel is baptism as dying entirely to self and rising entirely to Christ (Rom 6:3-4).</p>",
    "21": "<p>Moses washed the entrails and legs with water and burned the whole ram on the altar — a <strong>reyach nichoch laYHWH</strong> (<em>rêaḥ nîḥōaḥ laYHWH</em>), &ldquo;a pleasing aroma to YHWH.&rdquo; The same phrase describes Christ's sacrifice in Eph 5:2: &ldquo;Christ loved us and gave himself up for us, a fragrant offering and sacrifice to God.&rdquo; The pleasing aroma language signals divine acceptance; the offering is received, not merely performed.</p>",
    "22": "<p>The second ram is the <strong>milu'im</strong> (<em>millûʾîm</em>, ordination/fillings) ram — a term unique to this ritual; <em>millûʾîm</em> literally means &ldquo;fillings&rdquo; or &ldquo;investments&rdquo;; it refers both to the filling of the priests' hands with offerings (v27) and to the complete investiture of the office. The ordination ceremony is a &ldquo;filling&rdquo; — the new priests are both invested and equipped, their hands literally filled with what they need for service.</p>",
    "23": "<p>Moses put blood on the <strong>lobe of Aaron's right ear</strong> (<em>tenûk ōzen Ahărōn hᵉyāmānît</em>), the <strong>thumb of his right hand</strong> (<em>bōhen yādô hᵉyāmānît</em>), and the <strong>big toe of his right foot</strong> (<em>bōhen raglô hᵉyāmānît</em>) — blood on the ear (to hear YHWH's commands), the hand (to do YHWH's work), and the foot (to walk in YHWH's ways); the whole person dedicated to YHWH's service through blood-consecration at every extremity. The pattern mirrors the cleansing of the recovered leper (Lev 14:14) — priest and healed-leper are consecrated by the same blood-to-extremities pattern.</p>",
    "24": "<p>Moses put blood on the right ear-lobe, thumb, and big toe of Aaron's sons as well — the entire priestly cohort receives the threefold blood-anointing; consecration is not only for the high priest but for all who serve in the sanctuary. 1 Pet 1:2: those who are &ldquo;sprinkled with his blood&rdquo; form the entire new covenant priesthood (1 Pet 2:9), all consecrated at their extremities through Christ's atoning blood.</p>",
    "25": "<p>Moses took the fat, the fat tail, the fat on the entrails, the liver lobe, the two kidneys with fat, and the right thigh — the choicest internal portions and the right thigh set aside as YHWH's premier portion. The systematic identification of the best portions for YHWH across all animal offerings establishes the theological principle: the first and best belongs to God (Prov 3:9 &ldquo;honor YHWH with your firstfruits&rdquo;).</p>",
    "26": "<p>Moses added to the fat one unleavened loaf, one loaf with oil, and one wafer from the basket of unleavened ordination bread — the grain offering (<em>minḥāh</em>) accompanies the animal offerings; bread + animal = the full human food-offering; both the labor of the field and the labor of the flock are presented. Christ as both the bread of life (John 6:35) and the Lamb of God (John 1:29) fulfills both dimensions.</p>",
    "27": "<p>Moses placed all these in the hands of Aaron and his sons and waved them as a <strong>tenufah</strong> (<em>tᵉnûpāh</em>, wave offering) before YHWH — the waving gesture presents the offering before YHWH and signifies his reception and return of what belongs to him. The priests' hands are literally &ldquo;filled&rdquo; (<em>millûʾîm</em>) with the offerings — hence ordination is called the filling of the hands; the priest is a mediating conduit between YHWH and the offering.</p>",
    "28": "<p>Moses then took the wave offerings from the priests' hands and burned them on the altar on top of the burnt offering — the ordination sacrifices are placed on top of the already-burning burnt offering; the ordination is built on the foundation of total consecration (burnt offering = total devotion). Ministry rests on prior whole-life dedication.</p>",
    "29": "<p>Moses took the breast (<em>ḥāzeh</em>) and waved it as a wave offering before YHWH — Moses's portion of the ordination ram, taken as the officiating priest's share. In this unique ceremony, Moses acts as the ordaining priest before the Aaronic priesthood exists; he performs a priestly function that only he can perform. The chapter marks a transition: the one mediator (Moses) installing the ongoing mediation of the Aaronic priesthood.</p>",
    "30": "<p>Moses sprinkled anointing oil and blood on Aaron, his sons, and their garments — <strong>oil + blood</strong> together; the dual element of consecration: oil (<em>šemen</em>, anointing/Spirit) and blood (<em>dām</em>, atonement) constitute complete priestly consecration. Heb 9:21 notes that Moses &ldquo;sprinkled with the blood both the tent and all the vessels used in worship.&rdquo; The new covenant antitype: Spirit and blood both applied to the believer-priest (1 John 5:6-8).</p>",
    "31": "<p>Aaron and his sons are commanded to boil the ordination flesh at the entrance of the tent and eat it there with the ordination bread — the covenant meal at the end of the ordination; eating in the presence of YHWH seals the covenant relationship begun in the ceremony. The priestly ordination meal is a type of the Lord's Supper as the covenant meal of the new covenant priesthood (1 Cor 10:16-17).</p>",
    "32": "<p>What remains of the flesh and bread is to be burned with fire — nothing of the ordination sacrifice may be taken away and profaned outside the sacred precinct; the completeness-of-devotion principle: what is given to YHWH is given entirely. The prohibition against leftovers prevents the holy from mingling with the common.</p>",
    "33": "<p>Aaron and his sons shall remain at the entrance of the tent for <strong>seven days</strong> (<em>šibeʿat yāmîm</em>), for it takes seven days to complete the ordination (<em>milu'im</em>) — the seven-day period corresponds to the seven days of creation; the ordination ritual creates a new order of priestly ministry. Only after the full seven-day formation period may the priests begin public ministry; preparation precedes service throughout Scripture (cf. Jesus's forty days of testing before his public ministry, Luke 4:1-14).</p>",
    "34": "<p>&ldquo;As has been done today, YHWH commanded to be done <strong>lekapper aleichem</strong>&rdquo; (<em>lᵉkappēr ʿᵃlêkem</em>): &ldquo;to make atonement for you.&rdquo; The entire seven-day ordination process is fundamentally an atonement-making procedure for the priests themselves; priests require atonement before they can make atonement for others. The Aaronic priesthood is structurally dependent on sacrificial atonement. Christ, by contrast, &ldquo;offered himself unblemished to God&rdquo; (Heb 9:14) — his ordination required no atonement because he was the sinless ordainer and the sinless offering simultaneously.</p>",
    "35": "<p>Aaron and his sons shall remain at the entrance day and night for seven days, performing YHWH's charge &ldquo;so that you do not die&rdquo; — the threat of death for deviation from the ordained process; the holiness of the divine prescription carries mortal weight. The death-threat is the measure of the seriousness of the encounter with the holy God. Heb 12:28-29 applies the same logic: acceptable worship requires reverence and awe because our God is a consuming fire.</p>",
    "36": "<p>&ldquo;And Aaron and his sons did all the things that YHWH commanded by Moses&rdquo; — the chapter closes with comprehensive obedience; &ldquo;all the things&rdquo; emphasizes completeness, leaving no element unperformed. The obedient conclusion validates the entire ceremony. Christ: &ldquo;I have accomplished the work that you gave me to do&rdquo; (John 17:4) — the same complete obedience that validated the new covenant ordination.</p>"
  },
  "9": {
    "1": "<p>On the <strong>yom hashemini</strong> (<em>yôm haššᵉmînî</em>), the eighth day — the number eight in biblical numerology signals a new beginning beyond the seven of completion; circumcision on the eighth day (Lev 12:3), resurrection on the first/eighth day of the week. The eighth day of priestly ordination is the dawn of the new era of active ministry after the seven-day formation; the new creation begins when consecration is complete.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Aaron is instructed to bring a <strong>ben baqar</strong> (<em>ben bāqār</em>, a young bull/calf) for his sin offering — the same category of animal as his ordination sin offering (8:14); the high priest's inaugural service begins where his ordination began: with his own sin offering. The permanent structural need of the Aaronic high priest for personal atonement before every service is Hebrews' central argument for Christ's superiority (Heb 7:27-28).</p>",
    "3": "<p>The people bring a male goat (<em>śᵉʿîr ʿizzîm</em>) for a sin offering and a calf and a lamb for burnt offerings — the full suite of atonement and devotion offerings for the community on the inaugural day of priestly service. The variety of animals and offerings reflects the comprehensive scope of the relationship being inaugurated: sin covered, total devotion expressed.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The <strong>shelem</strong> (<em>šᵉlāmîm</em>, peace/fellowship offering; from <em>šālôm</em>) is the culminating offering of the inaugural day — the peace offering is the goal of the entire sacrificial system: atonement secured (sin offering) + devotion expressed (burnt offering) = fellowship enjoyed (peace offering). &ldquo;YHWH will appear to you&rdquo; (<em>niraʾ ʾalêkem YHWH</em>) is the stated purpose; all the rituals exist for the sake of the divine appearance.</p>",
    "5": "<p>All the congregation drew near and stood before YHWH — <strong>qarov</strong> (<em>qārᵃbû</em>, they drew near); the technical verb of priestly approach is here applied to the entire congregation; the priestly ritual brings the whole community into YHWH's presence, not just the priest. The corporate character of Israel's worship: the individual priest mediates for the whole, who are themselves drawn near.</p>",
    "6": "<p>&ldquo;That the <strong>kevod YHWH</strong> (<em>kᵉbôd YHWH</em>) may appear to you&rdquo; — the glory of YHWH is the stated goal of the entire day's ritual. The <em>kāvôd</em> (weighty presence, glory) is what the tabernacle, priesthood, and sacrifice all exist to mediate. John 1:14: &ldquo;we have seen his glory, glory as of the only Son from the Father&rdquo; — the Incarnation is the ultimate appearance of the divine glory that Lev 9 promises.</p>",
    "7": "<p>&ldquo;<strong>Qarav el hamizbeach</strong>&rdquo; (<em>qᵉrav ʾel-hammizbêaḥ</em>): &ldquo;draw near to the altar&rdquo; — Aaron's first official act is the technical priestly motion of approach. <em>Qarav</em> (to draw near/approach) is the defining verb of priestly worship throughout Leviticus; the priest is the one who is permitted to draw near where others would die. Heb 4:16: &ldquo;let us therefore draw near (<em>proserchōmetha</em>) with confidence to the throne of grace&rdquo; — the new covenant opens to all what the altar of Lev 9 permitted only to Aaron.</p>",
    "8": "<p>Aaron drew near to the altar and killed the calf of his own sin offering — his first official act as functioning high priest is self-atonement; the inaugural ministry begins with personal sin offering before any act on the people's behalf. The logic of Heb 7:27 is inescapable: the Aaronic high priest must always begin with himself; Christ began with himself as the offering, not as one needing the offering.</p>",
    "9": "<p>Aaron dipped his finger in the blood and put it on the <strong>horns of the altar</strong> (<em>qarnôt hammizbêaḥ</em>) and poured the rest at the base — the finger-dab application of sin-offering blood to the four altar horns is the distinctive application pattern of the sin offering; the horns (power-points) of the altar are the location where atonement blood is applied, and the base-pour returns excess blood to the ground.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The fat portions (<em>ḥēlev</em>), kidneys, and liver lobe were burned on the altar as YHWH commanded — the prescribed portions for YHWH from every offering; burning these choice pieces on the altar is the act of giving the best to God. Ps 63:5: &ldquo;my soul will be satisfied as with fat and rich food&rdquo; — the <em>ḥēlev</em> is the OT's symbol of the richest blessing; giving it to YHWH is offering the finest.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The flesh and skin of the sin offering bull were burned outside the camp — the sin offering whose blood was not brought into the inner sanctuary is disposed of outside the camp (cf. 6:30 where offerings whose blood enters the sanctuary are burned inside; 10:17-18 revisits this distinction). Heb 13:11-13 interprets this type: &ldquo;Jesus also suffered outside the gate.&rdquo;</p>",
    "12": "<p>Aaron killed the burnt offering (<em>ʿōlāh</em>) and his sons dashed the blood against the sides of the altar — the transition from sin offering (atonement) to burnt offering (devotion) follows the prescribed sequence: first make atonement, then present total devotion. The order is theologically determinative: the cross (atonement) precedes the consecrated life (devotion).</p>",
    "13": "<p>Aaron's sons handed him the burnt offering piece by piece and the head — the systematic dismemberment and burning of every part of the burnt offering; piece by piece, nothing held back; thorough and complete. The total devotion of the burnt offering is the OT's image of what Rom 12:1 commands: &ldquo;present your bodies as a living sacrifice.&rdquo;</p>",
    "14": "<p>Aaron washed the entrails and legs with water before burning them on the altar — the inward parts must be clean before being offered; the offering is both outwardly and inwardly pure. Christ, the true burnt offering, was pure within and without: &ldquo;holy, innocent, unstained&rdquo; (Heb 7:26); his inner life matched his outer righteousness.</p>",
    "15": "<p>Aaron offered the people's sin offering goat and made atonement for the people — the priestly service for the community follows the priestly service for the self. Aaron first atoned for himself (vv 8-11), then turns to the people. Heb 5:3: &ldquo;because of this he is obligated to offer sacrifice for his own sins just as he does for those of the people&rdquo; — the Aaronic sequence that Christ's priesthood transcends.</p>",
    "16": "<p>Aaron presented the burnt offering <strong>kashmishpat</strong> (<em>kammišpāṭ</em>): &ldquo;according to the rule/ordinance&rdquo; — the offering is validated by its conformity to the prescribed procedure; the rule is not an obstacle but the form of acceptable worship. Jesus: &ldquo;in accordance with the Scriptures&rdquo; (1 Cor 15:3-4) — his death and resurrection are likewise validated by conformity to the divine prescription.</p>",
    "17": "<p>Aaron presented the grain offering (<em>minḥāh</em>), took a handful, and burned it on the altar alongside the morning burnt offering — the grain offering expresses devotion through the work of human hands (harvested, ground, baked, offered); it complements the animal offering by adding the human-labor dimension. The full offering combines animal blood and human agricultural labor — the whole created order in service to God.</p>",
    "18": "<p>Aaron slaughtered the ox and ram as <strong>shelamim</strong> (<em>šᵉlāmîm</em>, peace/fellowship offerings) for the people — the peace offering is the goal and culmination of the entire sequence; its name from <em>šālôm</em> (wholeness, peace, well-being) names what it effects: restored relationship, fellowship, and wholeness between Israel and YHWH. The eschatological banquet (Rev 19:9) is the ultimate peace offering — the meal of permanent fellowship.</p>",
    "19": "<p>Aaron's sons handed him the blood of the peace offering, and he dashed it against the sides of the altar all around — the vigorous blood-dash of the peace offering completes the blood-ritual of the day; blood marks every altar-surface as the meeting point of divine holiness and human sinfulness resolved by sacrifice.</p>",
    "20": "<p>The fat pieces were placed on the breasts and burned on the altar — YHWH's portion (the fat) and the priestly portion (the breast) are both presented before YHWH before being distributed; the waving and burning that follows (v21) enacts the exchange between YHWH and his priests.</p>",
    "21": "<p>Aaron waved the <strong>chazeh hatenufa</strong> (<em>ḥāzeh hattᵉnûpāh</em>, wave breast) and the <strong>shoq hayamin</strong> (<em>šôq hayāmîn</em>, right thigh) as a wave offering — the breast and right thigh are the priests' statutory portions from every peace offering; the wave offering presents them to YHWH and receives them back as his gift to the priests. The workers are sustained by the work they serve; 1 Tim 5:18: &ldquo;the laborer deserves his wages.&rdquo;</p>",
    "22": "<p>Aaron <strong>lifted his hands toward the people and blessed them</strong> (<em>wayyiśśāʾ ʾahărōn ʾet yādāyw ʾel hāʿām waybārᵃkēm</em>) — the high-priestly benediction is the culmination of the entire day's service; the Aaronic blessing (Num 6:24-26) is the priest's primary gift to the people. Luke 24:50-51: Jesus &ldquo;lifting up his hands he blessed them. While he blessed them, he parted from them&rdquo; — the ascending Christ performs the high-priestly benediction over his disciples, the new covenant fulfillment of Aaron's lifted hands.</p>",
    "23": "<p>&ldquo;The <strong>kevod YHWH</strong> (<em>kᵉbôd YHWH</em>) appeared to all the people&rdquo; — the stated goal of v6 is achieved; YHWH manifests his presence in visible glory to the entire congregation. The divine glory appearing to &ldquo;all the people&rdquo; democratizes the theophany; ordinarily the divine presence is restricted (only the high priest enters the most holy place); here it is publicly manifested. John 1:14: &ldquo;we have seen his glory&rdquo; — the Incarnation is the ultimate democratic theophany, the divine glory made publicly visible.</p>",
    "24": "<p><strong>Vatetzei esh milifnei YHWH</strong> (<em>wattēṣēʾ ʾēš milᵉpānê YHWH</em>): &ldquo;fire came out from before YHWH&rdquo; and consumed the burnt offering — the theophanic fire is YHWH's sign of acceptance, the same fire that later consumes Nadab and Abihu for unauthorized worship (10:2); the same divine fire blesses complete obedience and destroys presumptuous deviation. The people's response: they shouted (<em>yāronnû</em>) and fell on their faces (<em>wayyippeḷû ʿal pᵉnêhem</em>) — the mixed response of joy and awe before the holy God. Heb 12:28-29: &ldquo;our God is a consuming fire.&rdquo;</p>"
  },
  "10": {
    "1": "<p>Nadab and Abihu offered <strong>esh zarah</strong> (<em>ʾēš zārāh</em>): &ldquo;unauthorized/strange/foreign fire&rdquo; — <em>zārāh</em> means strange, foreign, not belonging; the fire they offered was not the fire from YHWH's altar (16:12 specifies that the high priest must take coals from the altar before YHWH). Their error may have been the fire's origin, the incense formula, the timing, or acting outside their priestly brief — the text does not specify; what matters is the phrase &ldquo;which he had not commanded them&rdquo; (<em>ʾăšer lōʾ ṣiwwāh ʾōtām</em>). Unauthorized worship, however sincere or beautiful, is not acceptable to the holy God.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Fire from before YHWH consumed Nadab and Abihu — the same <em>ʾēš</em> (fire) that accepted the inaugural offering in 9:24 destroys the priests who violated the holy; the divine consuming fire is not primarily a tool of judgment but an expression of YHWH's holiness that both blesses obedience and destroys transgression. Heb 12:29: &ldquo;our God is a consuming fire&rdquo; — the NT draws on this episode to ground the call to reverent, acceptable worship.</p>",
    "3": "<p>&ldquo;<strong>Biqrovai ekadesh</strong>&rdquo; (<em>biqrōbay ʾeqqādēš</em>): &ldquo;among those who are near me I will be sanctified&rdquo; — YHWH declares the theological principle Nadab and Abihu violated: proximity to YHWH increases, not decreases, the demand for holiness. Those nearest to the fire feel its full heat. &ldquo;Before all the people I will be glorified&rdquo; (<em>wᵉʿal pᵉnê kol hāʿām ʾekkābēd</em>): YHWH's glory is upheld through the deaths of Nadab and Abihu; the people learn the cost of irreverence. 1 Pet 3:15: &ldquo;sanctify (<em>hagiasate</em>) Christ as Lord in your hearts&rdquo; — the same <em>qādaš</em> verb applied to the new covenant community's obligation.</p>",
    "4": "<p>Moses summoned Mishael and Elzaphan (Aaron's cousins) to carry the bodies outside the camp — the dead priests were removed in their priestly coats; non-ordained relatives handle what the surviving priests (Aaron and sons) may not touch during service. The separation of grief and ministry is painfully enforced; YHWH's service does not pause for human sorrow.</p>",
    "5": "<p>Mishael and Elzaphan carried the bodies outside the camp <strong>in their coats</strong> (<em>bᵉkuttōnōtām</em>) — the priestly vestments become shrouds; the garments that signified consecration and life now wrap death. The bodies are taken to the outside-the-camp location — the place of what is condemned, discarded, and burned. Heb 13:13: &ldquo;let us go to him outside the camp and bear the reproach he endured.&rdquo;</p>",
    "6": "<p>Moses forbids Aaron and his surviving sons to uncover their heads (<em>rōʾšêkem ʾal tipraʿû</em>) or tear their clothes (<em>ubigdêkem lōʾ tiphrōmû</em>), lest they die — the usual mourning rites (loose hair, torn clothes) are prohibited for the priests during their active service; their anointing has created an obligation that overrides natural family grief. The <strong>shemen hamishchah</strong> (<em>šemen hammiššāḥ</em>) upon them binds them to a higher call than private emotion.</p>",
    "7": "<p>&ldquo;The <strong>shemen mishchat YHWH</strong> (<em>šemen miššaḥat YHWH</em>) is upon you&rdquo; — the anointing creates a new identity overriding all prior obligations; the consecrated person belongs to YHWH's service above all else. Rom 12:1: &ldquo;present your bodies as a living sacrifice&rdquo; — the new covenant anointing (the Spirit) consecrates the believer to a service that claims all of life.</p>",
    "8": "<p>YHWH spoke directly to Aaron — notably, this is one of the rare moments in Leviticus when YHWH addresses Aaron directly rather than through Moses; the command that follows (vv 9-11) is given to the high priest as the direct recipient. After the trauma of his sons' deaths, YHWH speaks to Aaron personally, entrusting him with the principle that explains what happened.</p>",
    "9": "<p>&ldquo;<strong>Yayin veshekhar al tishteh</strong>&rdquo; (<em>yayyin wᵉšēkār ʾal tište</em>): &ldquo;wine and strong drink you shall not drink&rdquo; — the priest must approach YHWH with faculties unimpaired; <em>šēkār</em> is fermented drink stronger than wine; the prohibition applies specifically when entering the tent of meeting for ministry. Eph 5:18: &ldquo;do not get drunk with wine... but be filled with the Spirit&rdquo; — the NT's counterpart: the Spirit-filled, not wine-altered, is the proper state for worship; the prohibition of wine is a positive prescription for Spirit-dependence.</p>",
    "10": "<p>&ldquo;To <strong>havdil</strong>&rdquo; (<em>lᵉhavdîl</em>): &ldquo;to distinguish/separate&rdquo; — between <em>haqodesh</em> (the holy) and <em>hachol</em> (the common), and between <em>hatame</em> (the unclean) and <em>hatahor</em> (the clean). The root <em>bādal</em> (to separate) is the verb of creation itself (Gen 1:4, 6, 7, 14, 18 — God separates light from dark, waters from waters); the priest perpetuates the creation-work of differentiation, maintaining ordered distinctions within the sanctuary. Heb 5:14: &ldquo;mature believers trained by constant practice to distinguish (<em>diakrínein</em>) good from evil&rdquo; — the priestly discernment function extends to the new covenant community.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The priests are to <strong>teach Israel all the statutes</strong> (<em>ulᵉhôrôt ʾet bᵉnê yiśrāʾēl ʾēt kol haḥuqqîm</em>) — the priests' teaching function is inseparable from their ritual function; those who maintain the distinctions (v10) also explain and transmit them. Jer 31:34 promises that in the new covenant &ldquo;they shall all know me, from the least of them to the greatest&rdquo; — the new covenant distributes the priestly teaching function to all; Christ is the one Teacher (Matt 23:10) through whom all the <em>tôrāh</em> is rightly understood.</p>",
    "12": "<p>Moses addressed &ldquo;the remaining ones&rdquo; (<strong>hanotar'im</strong>, <em>hānôtārîm</em>) — Eleazar and Ithamar; the Levitical line narrows from four sons to two in a single day; the text marks the reduction without softening it. The priestly succession continues despite the loss; YHWH's program of priestly mediation is not derailed by human failure.</p>",
    "13": "<p>&ldquo;Eat it in a holy place (<em>māqôm qādôš</em>), for it is your <strong>choq</strong>&rdquo; (<em>ḥōq</em>, statutory due) — the priests' food from YHWH's fire offerings is their permanent statutory portion (<em>ḥōq</em> from the root of &ldquo;inscribed/decreed&rdquo;); it is written into the law's permanent structure. The eating is a priestly act of service, not merely sustenance; receiving the holy food is itself a sacred act.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The wave breast (<em>ḥāzeh hattᵉnûpāh</em>) and the heave thigh may be eaten in a <strong>makom tahor</strong> (<em>māqôm ṭāhôr</em>), a clean (but not necessarily holy) place — the degree of sanctity of the food determines where it may be eaten; the most holy portions require the holy place; the less restricted portions require only a clean place. The entire priestly food system involves graduated holiness, matching the tabernacle's spatial gradations.</p>",
    "15": "<p>The right thigh and wave breast are given as the priests' permanent portion to wave before YHWH — the <em>tᵉrûmāh</em> (contribution/heave offering; from <em>rûm</em>, to lift/elevate) and the <em>tᵉnûpāh</em> (wave offering) together constitute the priests' statutory share. The offering is first presented to YHWH and received back — the pattern of divine gift through human mediation that characterizes the entire sacrificial system.</p>",
    "16": "<p>Moses learned the sin-offering goat had been burned instead of eaten — he &ldquo;diligently inquired&rdquo; (<em>dārōš dāraš</em>, intensive form: thoroughly sought); Moses's careful oversight of every sacrificial detail reflects the seriousness with which YHWH's prescriptions are maintained. The doubled verb (<em>dārōš dāraš</em>) signals intensive action: Moses didn't casually notice but actively investigated.</p>",
    "17": "<p>&ldquo;Why have you not eaten the sin offering in the place of the sanctuary?&rdquo; — Moses's rebuke establishes the principle: eating the sin offering (<em>ʾăkal ʾet haḥaṭṭāʾt</em>) is part of the atonement act itself; the priests bear the congregation's iniquity (<em>yiśśᵉʾû ʾet ʿăwōn hāʿēdāh</em>) by eating it. The priestly eating of the sin offering is a vicarious act — the priest absorbs the sin symbolically. Christ as the ultimate sin-bearer: &ldquo;he himself bore our sins in his body on the tree&rdquo; (1 Pet 2:24).</p>",
    "18": "<p>Since the goat's blood was not brought inside the sanctuary, it should have been eaten by the priests in the sanctuary — the distinction that determines eating vs. burning: blood brought inside (most holy place) = carcass burned outside; blood not brought inside = carcass eaten by priests inside. The blood's trajectory determines the flesh's disposition; atonement ritual logic is precise and internally consistent.</p>",
    "19": "<p>Aaron's explanation: &ldquo;Such things as these have happened to me&rdquo; — on the day his two sons were killed, eating the sin offering in a state of grief would have been improper; Aaron invokes the theological principle that the worshiper's heart-state affects the acceptability of the ritual act. The law here accommodates the weight of human grief rather than crushing it; the pastoral wisdom beneath the legal prescription.</p>",
    "20": "<p>&ldquo;Moses heard, and <strong>vayitav be'einav</strong>&rdquo; (<em>wayyîṭab bᵉʿênāyw</em>): &ldquo;it was good in his eyes&rdquo; — Moses accepted Aaron's explanation; the legal framework shows flexibility in extraordinary human circumstances. The law is not a mechanical system but a relational covenant that accommodates human reality. Heb 4:15: Christ as our high priest &ldquo;is able to sympathize with our weaknesses&rdquo; — the sympathetic high priest exercises pastoral wisdom rather than rigid legal application, fulfilling what Moses modeled here.</p>"
  },
  "16": {
    "2": "<p>Yom Kippur (Day of Atonement) is the annual reset of Israel's covenant relationship: the accumulated sin of the year is dealt with by the high priest's double ritual — (1) the bull's blood for his own sin, (2) one goat killed for the people's sin (the sacrificed goat), (3) one goat bearing the sins symbolically into the wilderness (the scapegoat, <em>azazel</em>). The two-goat ritual together communicates the complete theology of atonement: blood-payment (the dead goat) + removal (the scapegoat). Christ fulfills both aspects: his blood makes propitiation and his bearing of sin removes it ('as far as the east is from the west, so far does he remove our transgressions from us', Ps 103:12).</p>"
  },
  "17": {
    "11": "<p><strong>ki nefesh habasar badam hi vaani netatihu lachem al hamizbeach lekapper al nafshoteichem ki hadam hu bakafra banefesh</strong>: 'For the life [<em>nefesh</em>] of the flesh is in the blood, and I have given it for you on the altar to make atonement for your souls [<em>nefesh</em>], for it is the blood that makes atonement by the life.' The blood-for-life exchange is the theological axiom underlying all sacrifice: blood (= life) offered for life (= the offerer's forfeit life). The principle is stated as divine appointment — 'I have given it for you on the altar' — sacrifice is not a human invention but a divinely ordained mechanism of atonement. Hebrews 9:22's 'without the shedding of blood there is no forgiveness of sins' is a direct application of Lev 17:11 to Christ's death.</p>"
  },
  "19": {
    "18": "<p><strong>veahavta lereiacha kamocha ani YHWH</strong>: 'You shall love your neighbor as yourself: I am YHWH.' The neighbor-love command concludes with the divine self-identification formula (<em>ani YHWH</em>) — the obligation is grounded not in a social contract but in YHWH's own character and authority. The scope of <em>rea</em> (neighbor) in Leviticus 19 extends throughout the chapter to include resident aliens (v. 34: 'love him as yourself, for you were aliens in Egypt'). Jesus's parable of the Good Samaritan expands the neighbor-category to include the unexpected outsider, but the Levitical warrant is already broader than its surface reading.</p>"
  }
}

CONTEXT = {
  "1": {
    "1": "<p>Leviticus is the central book of the Torah and the most liturgical: it contains the instructions for the five primary offerings (burnt, grain, peace, sin, guilt), the ordination of the Aaronic priesthood, the purity laws, the Holiness Code (chs. 17-26), and the festival calendar. Its context is the completed tabernacle (Exod 40) — YHWH's glory has filled the structure, and now YHWH speaks from within it (Lev 1:1: YHWH called to Moses and spoke to him from the tent of meeting). The book addresses the central problem of how a holy God can dwell among a sinful people — the answer is a complex system of sacrifice, priesthood, purification, and consecration. Hebrews reads Leviticus as the most detailed typological preparation for Christ's high-priestly work.</p>"
  },
  "16": {
    "1": "<p>Yom Kippur (the Day of Atonement, Lev 23:27-28) became the most solemn day in the Jewish calendar — the only mandatory communal fast in the Torah. In Second Temple Judaism, it was the one day the high priest entered the most holy place. When the temple was destroyed in 70 CE, the entire Yom Kippur sacrificial system became inoperative — Hebrews' argument that Christ's once-for-all sacrifice supersedes the annual Yom Kippur ritual became immediately relevant to Jewish Christians watching the temple system collapse. The phrase 'once for all' (<em>ephapax</em>, Heb 9:12; 10:10) is Hebrews' direct response to Yom Kippur's annual repetition.</p>"
  }
}

CHRIST = {
  "16": {
    "2": "<p>A fulfillment: 'YHWH said to Moses, Tell Aaron your brother not to come at any time into the Holy Place inside the veil, before the mercy seat that is on the ark, so that he may not die. For I will appear in the cloud over the mercy seat.' The entire Yom Kippur ritual — its restrictions, its blood-sprinkling, its once-per-year access, its careful approach protocol — is the OT's most detailed type of Christ's high-priestly work. Hebrews 9:1-14 maps the Yom Kippur elements onto Christ systematically: the holy of holies → heaven; the high priest → Christ; bull and goat blood → Christ's own blood; annual repetition → once for all; the mercy seat → Christ as <em>hilasterion</em> (Rom 3:25). Every element of Leviticus 16 is the shadow; Christ is the substance.</p>"
  },
  "17": {
    "11": "<p>A direct revelation: 'For the life of the flesh is in the blood, and I have given it for you on the altar to make atonement for your souls, for it is the blood that makes atonement by the life.' This verse is the theological axiom that explains why Christ had to die a bloody death — not a natural death, not a symbolic death, but a sacrificial death involving the shedding of blood. The divine appointment ('I have given it for you on the altar') means that blood-atonement is not a primitive accommodation to human psychology but a divine mechanism built into creation-order: life given for life, blood for blood. Christ's death fulfills this principle at its ultimate level: his blood, the blood of the God-man, atones not for one year or one nation but once for all humanity (Heb 9:12).</p>"
  },
  "19": {
    "18": "<p>A direct revelation: 'You shall love your neighbor as yourself: I am YHWH.' Jesus elevates Lev 19:18 to the second-greatest commandment (Matt 22:39) and Paul calls it the fulfillment of the whole law (Gal 5:14; Rom 13:9). But Christ does not merely cite the command — he embodies it: 'Greater love has no one than this, that someone lay down his life for his friends' (John 15:13). The neighbor-love of Lev 19:18 reaches its ultimate expression in the cross, where Christ loved his neighbors — his enemies — at the cost of his life (Rom 5:8: God demonstrates his love for us in that while we were still sinners, Christ died for us).</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    e = load_echo('leviticus')
    merge_echo(e, ECHO)
    save_echo('leviticus', e)

    c = load_comm('mkt-original', 'leviticus')
    merge_comm(c, ORIGINAL)
    save_comm('mkt-original', 'leviticus', c)

    c = load_comm('mkt-context', 'leviticus')
    merge_comm(c, CONTEXT)
    save_comm('mkt-context', 'leviticus', c)

    c = load_comm('mkt-christ', 'leviticus')
    merge_comm(c, CHRIST)
    save_comm('mkt-christ', 'leviticus', c)

    print('leviticus: all 4 layers written')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
